stigma will exist as long as the media enables it.

i say fucking ENOUGH.

lots of people say "we have to do better."

no.

YOU have to do better.

NDs have fought and fought for correct representation for FUCKING YEARS. and this is the thanks we get?

and not only that, but it keeps that goddamn anti-minority casting cycle going.

im ND myself. i've seen OCD be a quirky bit in TV shows. i didn't believe it when i was diagnosed with OCD, because i believed what the media i watched was portraying.

films like MUSIC are harmful.

there were neurodivergent actors available for this movie. there were minority actors available for ghost in the shell when fucking scarlett johansson was picked. 

don't say MUSIC is "inspiring" or "promotes diversity".

it only promotes stigma.

MUSIC was nominated for a fucking golden globe.

i doubt this is the first time a film innaccurately depicting a stigmatized group has been nominated for awards like these. but even one time, is one time too many. this teaches us that these movies are RIGHT in their depictions.

sia's film MUSIC casted a non-autistic actor to play an autistic character. it shows the character being forcibly restrained during a meltdown. restraining someone during a panic attack or meltdown can KILL.

and still, in the name of "diversity", MUSIC was nominated.

NDs everywhere - irl and online - have advocated for better understanding of autism and mental illnesses. we are loud as fuck about it. 

and the golden globes fuck us over by nominating a film that teaches neurotypicals to put ND lives in DANGER.

hearing a health professional assume i was ASHAMED about the possibility about having autism, shows that the stigma surrounding it is EVERYWHERE. 

this misconception teaches us that the norm is to be ashamed of your neurodivergency. THAT SHIT HAS TO CHANGE.

i hate the fucking stigma that surrounds even getting DIAGNOSED with autism. 

i was asking my doctor about getting a specialist to test me for it. she responded with, "Don't feel bad about having it!"

i hadn't felt bad about having autism in the first place.
